---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import Nav from '../../components/Nav.astro';

const run = {
  dataset: 'CUAD v1 (Atticus Project)',
  datasetUrl: 'https://www.atticusprojectai.org/cuad',
  model: 'anthropic/claude-sonnet-4.5',
  samplesPerCategory: 5,
  totalSamples: 20,
  categories: 4,
  date: '2026-04-18',
  categoryResults: [
    { category: 'Document Name',  count: 5, em: 1.00, contains: 1.00, f1: 1.00, conf: 0.97 },
    { category: 'Parties',        count: 5, em: 0.00, contains: 1.00, f1: 0.20, conf: 0.96 },
    { category: 'Effective Date', count: 5, em: 0.20, contains: 0.40, f1: 0.45, conf: 0.99 },
    { category: 'Governing Law',  count: 5, em: 0.60, contains: 0.60, f1: 1.00, conf: 0.99 },
  ],
  overall:                        { count: 20, em: 0.45, contains: 0.75, f1: 0.66, conf: 0.97 },
};
---

<Layout title="Nomos · Benchmarks" description="Honest numbers for extract<T> on the CUAD dataset. First run, 20 samples, Claude Sonnet 4.5.">
  <Nav current="/research/benchmarks" />

  <article class="reveal max-w-wide mx-auto px-6 md:px-10 py-16 md:py-24">
    <span class="font-mono text-[11px] uppercase tracking-[0.14em] text-mute">§ Research / Benchmarks</span>
    <h1 class="mt-4 max-w-[26ch]">How well does <span class="text-accent italic">extract&lt;T&gt;</span> actually work?</h1>

    <p class="mt-10 text-xl md:text-2xl max-w-prose text-sub font-serif" style="font-weight:400; line-height:1.45;">
      Nomos's thesis stands or falls on the LLM bridge. This page is
      where we put real numbers. The first run, on the
      <a href={run.datasetUrl} target="_blank">Atticus CUAD dataset</a>,
      tells an honest story: the model is great at structured field names,
      decent at governing law, and too verbose on parties and dates.
    </p>

    <!-- Run meta -->
    <div class="mt-12 grid md:grid-cols-4 gap-6 text-[14px]">
      <div>
        <span class="font-mono text-[11px] uppercase tracking-[0.14em] text-mute">Dataset</span>
        <p class="mt-1 font-serif text-lg" style="font-weight:500">{run.dataset}</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <span class="font-mono text-[11px] uppercase tracking-[0.14em] text-mute">Model</span>
        <p class="mt-1 font-mono text-[14px] text-ink">{run.model}</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <span class="font-mono text-[11px] uppercase tracking-[0.14em] text-mute">Samples</span>
        <p class="mt-1 text-ink">{run.totalSamples} ({run.samplesPerCategory} × {run.categories} categories)</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <span class="font-mono text-[11px] uppercase tracking-[0.14em] text-mute">Run date</span>
        <p class="mt-1 text-ink">{run.date}</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <hr class="my-14 border-rule" />

    <!-- Results table -->
    <section>
      <h2 class="font-serif mb-6">Results by category.</h2>

      <div class="border border-rule overflow-hidden bg-white">
        <div class="grid grid-cols-[2fr_0.8fr_0.8fr_1fr_0.8fr_0.8fr] gap-2 px-4 py-3 bg-cream border-b border-rule text-[11px] font-mono uppercase tracking-[0.14em] text-mute">
          <span>Category</span>
          <span class="text-right">n</span>
          <span class="text-right">EM</span>
          <span class="text-right">Contains</span>
          <span class="text-right">F1</span>
          <span class="text-right">Conf</span>
        </div>
        {run.categoryResults.map((c) => (
          <div class="grid grid-cols-[2fr_0.8fr_0.8fr_1fr_0.8fr_0.8fr] gap-2 px-4 py-3 border-b border-rule text-[14px]">
            <span class="font-serif" style="font-weight:500">{c.category}</span>
            <span class="text-right font-mono text-sub">{c.count}</span>
            <span class={`text-right font-mono ${c.em >= 0.8 ? 'text-accent' : c.em >= 0.5 ? 'text-ink' : 'text-mute'}`}>{c.em.toFixed(2)}</span>
            <span class={`text-right font-mono ${c.contains >= 0.8 ? 'text-accent' : c.contains >= 0.5 ? 'text-ink' : 'text-mute'}`}>{c.contains.toFixed(2)}</span>
            <span class={`text-right font-mono ${c.f1 >= 0.8 ? 'text-accent' : c.f1 >= 0.5 ? 'text-ink' : 'text-mute'}`}>{c.f1.toFixed(2)}</span>
            <span class="text-right font-mono text-sub">{c.conf.toFixed(2)}</span>
          </div>
        ))}
        <div class="grid grid-cols-[2fr_0.8fr_0.8fr_1fr_0.8fr_0.8fr] gap-2 px-4 py-3 text-[14px] bg-accent-bg">
          <span class="font-serif font-bold">Overall</span>
          <span class="text-right font-mono">{run.overall.count}</span>
          <span class="text-right font-mono text-accent font-bold">{run.overall.em.toFixed(2)}</span>
          <span class="text-right font-mono text-accent font-bold">{run.overall.contains.toFixed(2)}</span>
          <span class="text-right font-mono text-accent font-bold">{run.overall.f1.toFixed(2)}</span>
          <span class="text-right font-mono text-sub">{run.overall.conf.toFixed(2)}</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p class="mt-4 text-[13px] text-mute max-w-prose">
        <strong>EM</strong>: extracted string equals ground-truth (case-insensitive).
        <strong>Contains</strong>: extracted ⊆ gold or gold ⊆ extracted.
        <strong>F1</strong>: token-level F1 against best ground-truth.
        <strong>Conf</strong>: self-rated confidence from the model (0–1).
      </p>
    </section>

    <hr class="my-14 border-rule" />

    <!-- What this means -->
    <section class="grid md:grid-cols-[220px_1fr] gap-10">
      <div>
        <span class="font-mono text-[11px] uppercase tracking-[0.14em] text-mute">§ 02</span>
        <h2 class="mt-3 font-serif">What this means.</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="max-w-prose space-y-5">
        <p>
          <strong>Document Name</strong> is a 1.00/1.00 win. Field-name
          extraction is essentially solved by a good model with a clear
          schema.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Parties</strong> shows the gap between the LLM's
          semantics and CUAD's span convention. The model extracts the
          full party paragraph ("Centrack International, a Florida
          corporation…"); CUAD's answer is just the party name. Contains
          = 1.00 because the gold answer is always a substring of what
          the model returned. F1 = 0.20 because the model returned five
          extra words per sample.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Effective Date</strong> is where the schema needs work.
          The model returned long phrases ("This Agreement is entered
          into on January 13, 2005") instead of dates. A stricter
          Date-only schema would close most of this gap.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Confidence = 0.97</strong> across the board tells us
          the model is consistently sure of itself — even when it's
          wrong on exact match. This is why Nomos routes
          <code>confidence &lt; 0.95</code> extractions to a human: the
          model's own score is a ceiling, not a floor. The
          human-in-loop gate is the thing that makes over-confident
          outputs safe.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <hr class="my-14 border-rule" />

    <!-- Reproduce -->
    <section class="grid md:grid-cols-[220px_1fr] gap-10">
      <div>
        <span class="font-mono text-[11px] uppercase tracking-[0.14em] text-mute">§ 03</span>
        <h2 class="mt-3 font-serif">Reproduce.</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="max-w-prose space-y-4">
        <p>Clone the repo, install, and run the harness:</p>
        <pre class="astro-code border border-rule bg-white"><code>{`git clone https://github.com/sboghossian/nomos
cd nomos && npm install && npm run build

# Download CUAD (38MB) from Zenodo
curl -sL -o /tmp/cuad.zip \\
  "https://zenodo.org/record/4595826/files/CUAD_v1.zip?download=1"
unzip -oq /tmp/cuad.zip -d /tmp/cuad
cp /tmp/cuad/CUAD_v1/CUAD_v1.json /tmp/cuad.json

# Run the benchmark
export OPENROUTER_API_KEY=sk-or-...
node bench/cuad/harness.mjs \\
  --cuad /tmp/cuad.json \\
  --samples 5 \\
  --categories "Document Name,Effective Date,Parties,Governing Law" \\
  --model claude-sonnet-4-5`}</code></pre>
        <p class="text-[14px] text-mute">
          Results land in <code>bench/cuad/results/cuad-&lt;timestamp&gt;.json</code>.
          Raw per-item scores are included so anyone can audit our numbers.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <hr class="my-14 border-rule" />

    <!-- Roadmap -->
    <section class="grid md:grid-cols-[220px_1fr] gap-10">
      <div>
        <span class="font-mono text-[11px] uppercase tracking-[0.14em] text-mute">§ 04</span>
        <h2 class="mt-3 font-serif">Next runs.</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="max-w-prose space-y-3 text-[15px]">
        <p>— <strong>Scale</strong>: 50 samples × 10 categories = 500 extractions for a stabler mean.</p>
        <p>— <strong>Model comparison</strong>: Sonnet 4.5 vs Opus 4.7 vs GPT-5 vs Gemini 2.5 Pro on the same seed.</p>
        <p>— <strong>Schema discipline</strong>: compare loose vs strict schemas on Effective Date to quantify the schema-design payoff.</p>
        <p>— <strong>MAUD</strong>: run the same harness on M&amp;A questions (47k labels, 152 contracts).</p>
        <p>— <strong>ACORD</strong>: evaluate retrieval accuracy on 126k query-clause pairs.</p>
        <p class="mt-6 text-[13px] text-mute">
          All results here get posted verbatim — wins and losses. Nomos's credibility rides on the graph, not the hype.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>
  </article>
</Layout>
